<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>A Florida man has been charged with assault on a law enforcement officer after a scuffle around Senator Rand Paul as he left the White House following Donald Trump's speech to the RNC.</p>

<p>Paul and his wife were encircled by a crowd of protesters following Trump's address, and said they feared for their lives amid the 'crazed mob' of protesters.</p>

<p>'They were trying to push the police over to get to me,' he said. </p>

<p>'They were grabbing at us, and it got worse and worse and worse, and finally, we decided to make a move - they were shouting threats to us, to kill us, to hurt us.'</p>

<p>Rand Paul and his wife were confronted by protesters as they left the White House August 27</p>

<p>Crowds of people tussled with law enforcement, and one officer had to go to hospital</p>

<p>On Wednesday the Department of Justice announced that a man had been arrested following the incident.</p>

<p>Brennen Sermon, 27, of Orlando, Florida, was charged on August 28 - the day after Trump's speech.</p>

<p>Police claim that, shortly after midnight, a Metropolitan Police Department officer was holding a police line at 14 and F Street NW when a protester kicked his bicycle and fled. </p>

<p>The officer pursued, and police allege that Sermon punched the officer, who was left with a deep cut to his face and a severe swelling above his left eye.</p>

<p>The officer was taken to hospital, and received stitches. </p>

<p>If Sermon is convicted, he could face up to 180 days in prison. He could also face a fine of up to $1,000. </p>

<p>Paul, senator for Kentucky, said he feared for his life amid the 'attack' by the 'crazed mob'</p>
